elow 0.1mJy are hardly ever observed. In consequence, a single powerlaw or\nlognormal distribution does not suffice to describe the observed flux\ndistribution in its entirety. However, if one takes into account a power law\ncomponent at high flux densities, a lognormal distribution can describe the\nlower end of the observed flux distribution. We confirm the RMS-flux relation\nfor Sgr~A* and find it to be linear for all flux densities in our observation.\nWe conclude that Sgr~A* has two states: the bulk of the emission is generated\nin a lognormal process with a well-defined median flux density and this\nquiescent emission is supplemented by sporadic flares that create the observed\npower law extension of the flux distribution.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 15 Apr 2020 16:27:05 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Thu, 16 Apr 2020 15:45:46 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-07-01"}
